    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-04-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-04-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="622"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d622">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.50 Recovery/4–1549</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Director of the Office of Far Eastern
                        Affairs</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Butterworth</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-04-15">April 15,
                            1949</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The attached ECA telegram (To ECA 1340 April 13<note n="98" xml:id="d622fn98"
                        >Copy not found in Department of State files.</note>) indicates that the ECA
                    China Mission has been able to adjust its commodity procurement schedules under
                    the residual $53.7 million program so as to continue food and petroleum
                    deliveries substantially through the next harvest (September 15) without
                    disturbing $25 million of residual funds reserved for industry on Taiwan and for
                    continuation of the rural reconstruction program. This adjustment has been
                    accomplished by concentrating available commodity funds on cereals, cutting
                    petroleum deliveries to the bone, and eliminating raw cotton entirely. However,
                    the mission reports that the Chinese are developing plans for procurement of
                    cotton on their own account.</p>
                <p>The mission’s reference to CUSA (Chinese Government) concurrence in this program
                    indicates that ECA’s reservation of $25 million for other than commodity
                    procurement has been made known to the Chinese. This revelation would appear to
                    have been unnecessary under the China legislation as just passed by
                        Congress<note n="99" xml:id="d622fn99">Section 12 of Public Law 47, approved
                        April 19; 63 Stat 50, 55.</note> which authorizes the President to extend
                    aid in such manner and on such terms and conditions as he may determine.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W. W[<hi rend="smallcaps">alton</hi>] B[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >utterworth</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
